50|$|The anticenter {{shell is}} {{approximately}} 55,000 light years (17 kpc) from the sun. Its dimensions {{are difficult to}} determine by radio observation due to its location near the Zone of Avoidance, the regions of the sky obscured by interstellar dust along the <b>galactic</b> <b>equator.</b>|$|E
5000|$|Latitude (symbol [...] ) {{measures}} {{the angle of}} an object north or south of the <b>galactic</b> <b>equator</b> (or midplane) as viewed from Earth; positive to the north, negative to the south. For example, the north galactic pole has a latitude of +90°. Analogous to terrestrial latitude, galactic latitude is usually measured in degrees (°).|$|E
